LK-99
-----

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-08-02/superco=
nductor-breakthrough-buzz-spurs-china-korea-tech-rally ) :

Claims about a breakthrough in superconductor technology that could revolut=
ionize the power, transportation and chip industries have sparked surges in=
 some Korean and Chinese stocks even as scientists remain dubious. Small ca=
ps including Duksung Co., Sunam Co. and Shinsung Delta Tech Co. jumped by t=
heir 30% daily limits for a second-straight day in Seoul. In China, Jiangsu=
 Fasten Co. and Innovation New Material Technology Co. climbed by their 10%=
 limits for a second session.

Stocks seen as related to the technology have been rising since a July 22 r=
eport from South Korean researchers stating that they had synthesized the w=
orld=E2=80=99s first superconductor able to conduct electricity at room tem=
perature and ambient pressure. The superconductor utilizes a lead-based mat=
erial dubbed LK-99.

Take this segment for what it is: a heads-up about a bit of news that is pr=
obably not going to matter, but if it ends up mattering, will matter more t=
han almost anything. Over the last week there has been a mad dash to verify=
 some extraordinary claims from South Korea about the creation of a room-te=
mperature superconducting material named LK-99; your default assumption sho=
uld be that the claims will end up being false, given the large number of f=
alse alarms in this space in the past, and, frankly, the extraordinary impl=
ications entailed in the claim being true.

Over the last couple of days, though, several different groups and individu=
als have replicated LK-99=E2=80=99s diamagnetic properties =E2=80=94 the fa=
ct that it is repelled by both positive and negative magnetic fields; that =
is a property of superconductors, but not exclusively. In addition, a resea=
rcher at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory ( https://arxiv.org/abs/=
2307.16892 ) and researchers at the Shenyang National Laboratory for Materi=
als Science ( https://twitter.com/alexkaplan0/status/1686244162767552512?s=
=3D42&t=3D3jNRhFSsJkSBz7CjCSAX0g ) have run simulations showing that the pr=
oposed molecular structure of LK-99 has the properties of a potential super=
conductor.

To understand why this is a big deal, it=E2=80=99s useful to start with cin=
ema:

This image is from Avatar; the rock is =E2=80=9CUnobtanium=E2=80=9D, a room=
-temperature superconductor that is insanely valuable and the bedrock of hu=
man civilization, yet only available on Pandora, and it is floating because=
 it is diamagnetic. It=E2=80=99s a plausible premise! Superconductors condu=
ct electricity with perfect efficiency, which has all kinds of positive out=
comes: you could install solar panels in the desert, for example, and trans=
port the electricity thousands of miles away. You could build perfect batte=
ries. You could build magnetically levitating trains that move without fric=
tion. You could build fusion reactors. You could build quantum computers. S=
uperconductors do exist, but only at high pressure and extremely low temper=
atures that aren=E2=80=99t viable for widespread use; it=E2=80=99s that roo=
m-temperature (and room-pressure) bit that is potentially extraordinary abo=
ut LK-99.

Materials science and superconductors are, to be sure, far afield from my a=
reas of expertise, and again, your default assumption should be that LK-99 =
is probably not a superconductor, but rather some sort of other diamagnetic=
 material. I thought it worth bringing up in the Update, though, because if=
 it ends up being real, the implications are incredibly profound.

