The broader issue is that the video industry finally seems to be facing wha=
t happened to the print and music industry before them: the Internet comes =
bearing gifts like infinite capacity and free distribution, but those gifts=
 are a poisoned chalice for industries predicated on scarcity. When anyone =
could publish text, most text-based businesses went from massive profitabil=
ity to terminal decline; when anyone could distribute music the music indus=
try could only be saved by tech companies like Spotify helping them sell co=
nvenience in place of plastic discs.

For the video industry the first step to survival must be to retreat to wha=
t they are good at =E2=80=94 producing content that isn=E2=80=99t available=
 anywhere else =E2=80=94 and getting away from what they are not, i.e. runn=
ing undifferentiated streaming services with massive direct costs and even =
larger opportunity ones. Talent, meanwhile, has to realize that they and th=
e studios are not divided by this new paradigm, but jointly threatened: the=
 Internet is bad news for content producers with outsized costs, and long-t=
erm sustainability will be that much harder to achieve if the focus is on i=
ncreasing them.

Previous Hollywood strikes happened in a world of scarcity =E2=80=94 specif=
ically, there was nothing else to watch. Now there is more content than you=
 could ever consume in a lifetime, and that content is attached to some of =
the most finely honed advertising platforms ever. It=E2=80=99s certainly pl=
ausible that the primary factor keeping advertisers on traditional platform=
s was that that was the status quo; writers and actors changing said status=
 quo could be as big of an error as the studios self-cannibalizing TV with =
their ill-conceived streaming strategies.

